Employee Attrition Classification¶

Abstract¶

Employee attrition can have ruinous impact on the health of a company. Whenever an experience employee leaves the organization, there is a cost associated with it. A part of this cost is quantifiable numbers and the other part is hidden costs. The quantifiable cost includes the cost incurred in recruiting a replacement and training them. It would be great to have a machine learning model that will help the management to identify the employees who may potentially leave or quit. So that the management can take corrective measures to avoid employee attrition. The intend of the project is to use different classification models and tools available to accurately predict whether an employee will leave the company or not. The various classification techniques used in this project are Logistic Regression classifier, Support vector Machine classifier, Neural Networks and Ensemble methods (Decision Forests). The tools used are python in Jupyter note book and Microsoft Azure Machine Learning

Introduction¶

High employee attrition rate is a bad news for any organization. Employee turnover rate is number of employees who left during the entire year divided by the total number of employees at the beginning of the year and it is calculated annually. A high employee turnover may be risky for health of the company as high cost are associate with it. The quantifiable cost includes the cost involves recruiting, training etc. Generally, the productivity of the new hire is lower until he/she learn the business. For a customer facing role, if some customer/s are unhappy with the new hire, the business could lose customers who are dissatisfied with service leading to a loss in the revenue. Thus, it is very crucial for company’s management to understand the factors leading to employee attrition and to identify the potential employees who could quit and finally to institutionalized measures to reduce attrition rates.

There can be umpteen reasons for employee attrition. Many of these reasons are personal and may varies from person to person, it can be as diverse as different human personalities. But it is important to analyze some of the basic factors that triggers most resignations?

As discussed, the primary goal of this project is to correctly identify the potential employees in a company who could leave using a classification model.

Reasons for Employee Attrition¶

To take corrective measure to stop high attrition rate in an organization, it is important to analyze what are the factors that influences a person’s decision to quite the company. Here are some of the reasons, why an employee might leave his/her current job :-

  1. Mostly people leave their employer for an increased paycheck or career advancement,
  2. Many researches also shows that often the search for a new position is trigger due to dissatisfaction with an immediate manager.
  3. Employee are not engaged and they are bored. High-performing workers need to feel that they are being challenged and are moving forward in terms of professional growth and development.

About the Data¶

The dataset was downloaded from Kaggle repository.This is a fictional data set created by IBM data scientists to uncover the factors that lead to employee attrition and explore important questions such as ‘show me a breakdown of distance from home by job role and attrition’ or ‘compare average monthly income by education and attrition’. Some of variables used here are:

Education: 1 'Below College' 2 'College' 3 'Bachelor' 4 'Master' 5 'Doctor'
EnvironmentSatisfaction: 1 'Low' 2 'Medium' 3 'High' 4 'Very High'
JobInvolvement: 1 'Low' 2 'Medium' 3 'High' 4 'Very High'
JobSatisfaction: 1 'Low' 2 'Medium' 3 'High' 4 'Very High'
PerformanceRating:1 'Low' 2 'Good' 3 'Excellent' 4 'Outstanding'
RelationshipSatisfaction:1 'Low' 2 'Medium' 3 'High' 4 'Very High'
WorkLifeBalance: 1 'Bad' 2 'Good' 3 'Better' 4 'Best' JobLevel: 1 'Entry' 2 'Intermediate' 3 'Experienced' 4 'Advance' 5 'Expert'

The dataset has 1470 observation and 35 columns.
The dataset can be downloaded from kaggle website

Data Exploration and Visualization of Dataset¶

I have created the three functions EA_snsbox, EA_bar ,EA_VP for creating the boxplots and bar charts on various predictors variables

In [128]:
# Creates boxplots on the data
def EA_snsbox(df,col):
    import matplotlib
    import numpy as np
    import seaborn as sns
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    sns.set_style("dark")
    g=sns.boxplot(x="Attrition",y=col,data= df,palette="Set1")
    sns.plt.title('Box plot of ' + col + '\n for Employee Attrition')
    g.set_xticklabels(labels=df["Attrition"], rotation=90)
    
# creates the bar charts on the data
def EA_bar(df, cols):
    import seaborn as sns
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    pf=df.groupby([cols,"Attrition"]).size().reset_index(name='counts')
    sns.set_style("dark")
    g=sns.barplot(x=cols, y="counts",hue="Attrition", data=pf)
    sns.plt.title(cols +' vs. \n Employee Attrition')
    sns.plt.ylabel('Count')
    g.set_xticklabels(labels=np.unique(pf[cols]), rotation=90)
    
# Interaction between various variables
def EA_VP(df,col1,col2):
    import seaborn as sns
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    sns.set_style("dark")
    g = sns.violinplot(x=col1, y=col2, hue="Attrition",
                        data=df, palette="Set2", split=True,scale="count")
    sns.plt.title('Voilinplots: ' + col1 + 'Vs' + col2 + '\n for Employee Attrition')
    g.set_xticklabels(labels=np.unique(df[col1]), rotation=90)

Employee Attrition versus Age,Gender and Marital Status¶

Many studies have linked age, gender, and relationship status with job satisfaction. Like for example the senior citizen have the highest level of job satisfaction among the U.S. workers. It is generally believed that job satisfaction increases with age. So does it mean younger employee tends to quite jobs and seek another opportunity more than older folks. Are the woman folks more satisfied with their jobs or its other way around? Is there an empirical relationship between marital status and job satisfaction?

Let’s try the answer the above questions, by visually exploring the data of this fictitious company.

Work Life Balance¶

Work-life balance varies from person to person and from generation to generation of the workforce. Employers need to take into consideration the healthy work-life balance needs of each employee. Work-life balance programs can reduce employee turnover and improve recruitment, increasing the productivity. In this section, let’s explore relation between different factors like 'Distance from Home', 'Over-Time ‘, 'Work-Life balance’ and the employee attrition.

Pre-Processing of Dataset¶

It is important to pre-process the data before doing the actually analysis. This steps involves :-

1. Handling the missing data
2. Droping the redundant columns.
3. Scaling or Normalization of data (as needed)

1.Droping the redundant columns:

  • All the employees of company are over 18 years of age.
  • Standard Hours is constant value of 80
  • 'Employee Count' is always 1
  • 'Employee Number' - unique identification of employee.
  • The variables 'DailyRate','EducationField','HourlyRate', 'JobRole','MonthlyRate','YearsAtCompany','PerformanceRating' are columns of zero importance of our datasets (verified using Permutation Feature Importance Module IN Azure ML )
In [85]:

2.Coverting categorical data into number:

Many Machine Learning tools accept only numbers as input, this can cause a problem as the above dataset has some categorical predictor variables too. To convert them as number I have used the 'LabelEncoder'. To convert the nominal variables like ‘Marital status’, ‘Gender’,’OverTime’ etc. I used the 'One-Hot-encoder' form sklearn.preprocessing.

In [92]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder,OneHotEncoder
# Converting categorical values into numerical values
labelencoder_x= LabelEncoder()
for i in [1,2,6,10,13]:
    X.iloc[:, i]=labelencoder_x.fit_transform( X.iloc[:, i])
    
# creating columns for categorical values
onehotencoder =OneHotEncoder(categorical_features=[1,6,10,13])
X=onehotencoder.fit_transform(X).toarray() 
# yes/no into numerical values
Y=labelencoder_x.fit_transform(Y)

2. Logistic Regression¶

Before apply the Logistic Regression classifier and support vector Machine classifier, first we need to scale or normalized the data.

Logistic regression also known as logit regression is a regression model where the dependent variable is categorical variable. Here 'C' is inverse of regularization strength, smaller values specify stronger regularization. The function for tuning the parameters available in scikit-learn is called gridSearchCV() is used to get bets parameters.

param_grid: It is the dictionary or list with parameters names (string) as keys and lists of parameter settings to try as values. The penalty used is "l2"

In [101]:

3. Support Vector Machine Classifer¶

The class used for SVM classification in scikit-learn is svm.SVC(). The parameter for SVM classifier:

  1. C: It is the regularization parameter, C, of the error term.
  2. kernel: It specifies the kernel type to be used in the algorithm. It can be ‘linear’, ‘poly’, ‘rbf’, ‘sigmoid’, ‘precomputed’, or a callable. The default value is ‘rbf'.
  3. degree: It is the degree of the polynomial kernel function (‘poly’) and is ignored by all other kernels. The default value is 3.
  4. gamma: It is the kernel coefficient for ‘rbf’, ‘poly’, and ‘sigmoid’. If gamma is ‘auto’, then 1/n_features will be used instead.

The SVM is tune by changing parameters C, gamma and the kernel function. The function for tuning the parameters is called gridSearchCV(). param_grid: It is the dictionary or list with parameters names (string) as keys and lists of parameter settings to try as values.

Tunning of parameter

In [106]:

cv_preds.append(accuracy_score(Y_test, preds)*100)
print("Test accuracy %0.2f" % (100* accuracy_score(Y_test, preds)))

Test accuracy 86.73

Conclusion¶

All the models developed using Python Scikit learn for the project gave convincing test accuracy of about 86 to 89 %, which is pretty impressive. The HR department of the company can use the models to predict whether an employee is likely to quit his/her job. It is important dataset used for the experiment had only 1470 observation from a fictitious organization. More number of observation from a real organization can throw some more lights into the causes for employee attrition

The most important factors that causing most resignations in the company is “Overtime”, which is have already observed in the data-exploration section. About 30% of people who have do over-time have left their jobs. The business should not encourage overtime by efficiently tracking and managing employee time. One of the way to eliminate overtime is to cross-training across the team, so that the tasks are not individual-dependent.

It is also observed that the company has failed to retain its entry level people. To avoid the attrition of entry-level employees, take steps like training, attractive paychecks. While employee training and development can seem time consuming and inefficient, employee training for entry-level hires can ensure greater retention within the company and more competent coworkers down the line. In the data exploration section, we observe that the entry level employees are not paid very well. HR should take notice of it, the performance of entry–level employees should be evaluated on regular basis and high performing entry level employees should be rewarded by increasing their salaries or by giving promotion in the job role or both.

Job-satisfaction and Job Involvement are next big factors for retaining an employee. Keeping employees involve and satisfied takes more than just good pay and benefits. Management should ensure the employees are involved and satisfied with their job roles. The more involve is the employee less likely he/she quitting the job. Other important factors which the management should look into are:

• Business-travel: About 25% employee who have to travel frequently have left their jobs.

• Number of years spend with current manager and current role: It is observed that more the numbers of years with the current manager, the less an employee is likely to quite.

• Martial-Status: more single people are likely to quit their jobs than married or divorced people

It is interesting to note here is that the age of employee, percentage hike in Salary and training time spend does not have a very crucial role in the decision to quit the job in the company.
